{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "phenomenology-expert",
    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "No to line 17 note; one note at line 25 is sufficient",
    "content": "**No.** One note at line 25 is sufficient.\n\nReasoning: At line 17, the reader has not yet encountered Jing as a technical concept. It has not been introduced. A note saying \"境界 = boundary of Jing\" at that point would be prospective -- pointing forward to something the reader does not yet know. This creates cognitive noise: the reader would need to hold an unexplained term (\"Jing\") in suspension while reading a passage that is already doing substantial philosophical work (the argument about internal vs. external, the language-boundary analogy).\n\nThe author's own text introduces the technical 境 *later*, and the line 25 moment is where the transition naturally happens. A single note at line 25 can do both jobs simultaneously: \"境界 (here rendered 'horizon') literally combines 境 (Jing) and 界 (boundary). In this passage, the author shifts from 境界 to 境 alone -- the boundary drops away, and what remains is the structured experiential field that will be formalized as Jing (E) in the following sections.\"\n\nThis respects the reader's experience of the text as the author designed it: first encounter 境界 as \"horizon/bounds\" (natural, unforced), then witness the emergence of 境 from within it. Front-loading at line 17 would spoil the conceptual birth that makes line 25 powerful."
  }
}
